segments.text: We'll start.
Yes, for the team.
Identify yourself.
Okay, I'm Charles Paul.
I'm the director of the Bancroft Library.
And we're talking here at the Book Fair in San Francisco on September 8, 1996.
And we're talking about the future of libraries.
And I was just saying that at Bancroft, we shouldn't be collecting printed books.
We should be collecting unique archival materials, materials which by definition only exist in one format.
That's actually not so controversial, really.
So you explained it better.
It's a printed book.
Increasingly what's going to happen... But you're talking specifically about the Bancroft Library too, which is very clear.
You're not talking about the university library system by any way.

Well, I think that increasingly that's going to happen with universities because as material becomes digital, it doesn't matter where the physical copy is located because you can get access to it anywhere.
So if there are a thousand copies of a book, what difference does it make whether we have one, or it's at Stanford, or at the Houghton Library?
Once that book has been digitized and made available, then anybody can have access to it.
So we're talking unique items, of course, we would continue to... But we're interested, for example, we have the Mark Twain project.
So instead of looking for every edition of Mark Twain's works that have been published forever, we should be focusing on getting the manuscripts, the originals.
Because if they're lost...
They're gone forever.
How do you feel then about the next step then?
How about printed books that you already have, given an opportunity to digitize what you have?
Would you do that and then take steps to deaccession the printed books?
No, we'll never get rid of them because the book has an actual value that can be very useful for scholarship.
And the problem, of course, is that you never know what...
100 years down the line, someone who's going to be interested in.
But it's a question of where do you have a finite amount of resources.
So do you collect the stuff that everybody else has got, or do you focus on the things that only you can have?
So, just because the Bancroft Library should not be collecting printed books, you do feel that somebody should be?
Somebody should, absolutely.
I mean, our field is basically Western history.
You're talking strictly about, I mean, let's be clear that you're talking about your facility, your institution.
And so, we should be focusing, I think, on collecting materials.
I mean, Hubert Howe Bancroft was the founder of the library since then.
As I have heard.
As you well know.
As I have chronicled.
Thank you.
I love this book.
Almost by definition, there were no antiquary materials about California in the 19th century.
He collected the contemporary materials, because he knew that they were going to be useful not only for his own history, but in the future.
We should be collecting contemporary materials about California.
to make them available.
Such as, can you give me this?
Records of fraternal organizations, businesses, charitable organizations.
We have, I think, the classic is we have the Sierra Club.
So not necessarily literary things by any means.
We do California authors, but we have the Sierra Club audience.
I think that's absolutely wonderful.
I mean, what I would like to see is

also getting the business, especially the Chevron, and trying to look at their point of view about the environmental controversies of the past 30 or 40 years, so that, in fact, people can write about the environmental movement with material from both sides.
That's super.
This is great stuff.
So it isn't a question of, you know, the printed book is going to go away.
It's not going to go away.
Not in my lifetime, not in your lifetime, and not for a long, long time.
But it is, as a source of information, it is going to be replaced by the computer.
And I think that's the general feeling.
For literary works, I think for the foreseeable future, they're going to be in book form.
For scholarship, you want to make information available, and we would love to have
all of our stuff online, so people did not actually have to physically come into the Bancroft Library and use it.

Interestingly, in the Spanish imperial period, when business was being transacted, court cases were being transacted in Mexico, all through New Spain,
multiple sets of those were also made in manuscripts.
So one set was kept at the National Archives in Mexico, or at least ended up there.
Another set was sent back to Seville, and sometimes there were additional sets for various missions and various offices to help them have administrative control.
So there's another case where if one record is lost one place, there may at least be another manuscript copy of that record at another place in Bangkok.
